01:02:27.410 --> 01:02:29.380
So one of the first questions
that we have that's got a lot

01:02:29.380 --> 01:02:34.200
of votes, "When creating a
responsive sight, is it the

01:02:34.200 --> 01:02:38.730
best practice to define media
queries in pixels or Ems And

01:02:38.730 --> 01:02:42.040
are their pros and cons to
consider when using each of

01:02:42.040 --> 01:02:42.950
those?"

01:02:42.950 --> 01:02:47.530
BRAD FROST: Yeah, so there's
definitely advantages to

01:02:47.530 --> 01:02:52.930
defining your media queries in
relative units, like Ems.

01:02:52.930 --> 01:02:58.630
Lyza Danger Gardner of Cloud
Four wrote about this, about

01:02:58.630 --> 01:03:05.290
basically how proportional media
queries are a lot more

01:03:05.290 --> 01:03:06.200
future-friendly.

01:03:06.200 --> 01:03:07.780
But also, present-friendly.

01:03:07.780 --> 01:03:12.230
So in my experience,
I have seen pixel

01:03:12.230 --> 01:03:16.020
widths sort of destroyed.

01:03:16.020 --> 01:03:19.030
So a lot of different devices
handle pixels in a lot of

01:03:19.030 --> 01:03:20.110
different ways.

01:03:20.110 --> 01:03:23.890
16 pixels on a certain device
might look totally different

01:03:23.890 --> 01:03:27.020
than 16 pixels elsewhere.

01:03:27.020 --> 01:03:31.730
But also, user zoom settings
are really important.

01:03:31.730 --> 01:03:37.530
If I go into a responsive
website and command + +,

01:03:37.530 --> 01:03:41.110
magnify the site, which I
like to do actually--

01:03:41.110 --> 01:03:47.320
if your media queries are set in
pixels, it won't honor the

01:03:47.320 --> 01:03:48.530
user zoom settings.

01:03:48.530 --> 01:03:53.340
But if you handle them with
relative units using Ems, it

01:03:53.340 --> 01:03:54.770
will honor them.

01:03:54.770 --> 01:03:56.830
I think it requires
a page refresh.

01:03:56.830 --> 01:03:59.670
But at the same time, it
will re-flow the layout

01:03:59.670 --> 01:04:04.490
appropriately if you use
proportional media queries.

01:04:04.490 --> 01:04:07.390
And the other thing that's worth
stating is that we're

01:04:07.390 --> 01:04:10.710
using proportional units for
everything else now.

01:04:10.710 --> 01:04:11.530
PETE LEPAGE: Yeah,
that's true.

01:04:11.530 --> 01:04:14.580
BRAD FROST: For layouts, for
fonts, for everything now.

01:04:14.580 --> 01:04:17.030
Just take it that one step
further and define your break

01:04:17.030 --> 01:04:20.630
points in relative units.

01:04:20.630 --> 01:04:20.900
PETE LEPAGE: Cool.

01:04:20.900 --> 01:04:24.520
So next question from Dan in
Amsterdam wants to know,

01:04:24.520 --> 01:04:27.900
"Should we take into account
a device bandwidth before

01:04:27.900 --> 01:04:30.720
serving content, especially
media assets to the device?

01:04:30.720 --> 01:04:33.750
If so, how should we
implement that?"

01:04:33.750 --> 01:04:37.740
BRAD FROST: Yeah, so there's a
lot of actually really recent

01:04:37.740 --> 01:04:39.630
things that have been coming up

01:04:39.630 --> 01:04:43.330
regarding sort of bandwidth.

01:04:43.330 --> 01:04:46.230
It's still really tricky
to detect bandwidth.

01:04:46.230 --> 01:04:49.560
We have sort of the navigation,
navigator

01:04:49.560 --> 01:04:51.590
connection type, and
stuff like that.

01:04:51.590 --> 01:04:53.090
But even that's not reliable.

01:04:53.090 --> 01:04:57.520
Anybody that's been on like
hotel Wi-Fi will probably know

01:04:57.520 --> 01:05:01.080
that 3G is oftentimes
faster than that.

01:05:01.080 --> 01:05:05.050
We can't make assumptions even
based on even knowing what

01:05:05.050 --> 01:05:07.240
kind of connection
type we have.

01:05:07.240 --> 01:05:14.230
So I'd say that it's best to
assume a slow, painfully slow

01:05:14.230 --> 01:05:19.960
connection by default and serve
up assets appropriately.

01:05:19.960 --> 01:05:22.520
Things like adaptive images--

01:05:22.520 --> 01:05:25.750
and there's a lot of different
solutions and stuff that's

01:05:25.750 --> 01:05:29.040
sort of coming down the pipes
with regards to the spec and

01:05:29.040 --> 01:05:30.460
stuff like that.

01:05:30.460 --> 01:05:35.240
But in the meantime, we have
tools like Picture Fill, which

01:05:35.240 --> 01:05:40.280
allows us to serve a small
image by default.

01:05:40.280 --> 01:05:42.690
But then whenever you reach
a certain break point or

01:05:42.690 --> 01:05:46.710
whatever, then load in
a larger image asset.

01:05:46.710 --> 01:05:49.510
Same thing with retina graphics
and stuff like that.

01:05:49.510 --> 01:05:53.620
Small by default, but then
conditionally load in a higher

01:05:53.620 --> 01:05:55.240
res version.

01:05:55.240 --> 01:05:58.390
But one of the most recent
things that has been pretty

01:05:58.390 --> 01:06:03.070
clever is that they're finding
that the image compression,

01:06:03.070 --> 01:06:08.620
like JPEG compression, is more
a factor in determining a

01:06:08.620 --> 01:06:09.980
device's bandwidth--

01:06:09.980 --> 01:06:16.020
or, I'm sorry, an image's size
than the dimensions of them.

01:06:16.020 --> 01:06:19.010
So everyone's freaking out about
retina screens and stuff

01:06:19.010 --> 01:06:20.190
like that now.

01:06:20.190 --> 01:06:23.930
And it's important to understand
that you could

01:06:23.930 --> 01:06:28.610
actually create larger images
with larger dimensions, but a

01:06:28.610 --> 01:06:32.240
lower compression and then just
simply scale them down

01:06:32.240 --> 01:06:36.110
and they'll look great on retina
displays, as well as

01:06:36.110 --> 01:06:37.810
just standard displays.

01:06:37.810 --> 01:06:43.300
And in some cases, the file
size of the enhanced--

01:06:43.300 --> 01:06:43.870
the bigger--

01:06:43.870 --> 01:06:45.600
PETE LEPAGE: Is even smaller.

01:06:45.600 --> 01:06:47.460
BRAD FROST: Even smaller than
the base image, which is

01:06:47.460 --> 01:06:49.410
pretty crazy.

01:06:49.410 --> 01:06:56.660
But yeah, image optimization,
other things like maps and

01:06:56.660 --> 01:07:01.180
other interactive components,
just don't include those

01:07:01.180 --> 01:07:02.310
things by default.

01:07:02.310 --> 01:07:04.390
Again, I was talking about
conditionally loading.

01:07:04.390 --> 01:07:07.440
I will give my little example.

01:07:07.440 --> 01:07:09.870
I have a demo of this
on the way.

01:07:09.870 --> 01:07:12.940
Hopefully I can share
it later on--

01:07:12.940 --> 01:07:15.140
of something like Google Maps.

01:07:15.140 --> 01:07:19.790
If you want to embed Google Maps
in your site, you have to

01:07:19.790 --> 01:07:22.240
iFrame in the embedded map.

01:07:22.240 --> 01:07:25.050
But for small screens, I would
actually argue that's not a

01:07:25.050 --> 01:07:26.750
very good experience.

01:07:26.750 --> 01:07:32.460
For one, a lot of major
smartphone platforms, like iOS

01:07:32.460 --> 01:07:38.710
and Android, will intercept
links to Google Maps and fire

01:07:38.710 --> 01:07:42.130
up the native mapping
application, which is a far

01:07:42.130 --> 01:07:44.670
better user experience
than anything

01:07:44.670 --> 01:07:45.840
on the web can provide.

01:07:45.840 --> 01:07:49.940
Again, it just has access
to more things.

01:07:49.940 --> 01:07:52.410
So I'd say that that's
the best experience.

01:07:52.410 --> 01:07:55.700
So the demo that I have
simply includes a

01:07:55.700 --> 01:07:58.420
link to Google Maps.

01:07:58.420 --> 01:08:03.900
And you could use the Google
Static Map API or whatever, to

01:08:03.900 --> 01:08:07.310
pull in a still or whatever,
if you want to.

01:08:07.310 --> 01:08:11.270
And then whenever the screen
size becomes big enough, then

01:08:11.270 --> 01:08:14.120
you can load in that iFrame and
add an editable map and

01:08:14.120 --> 01:08:14.880
stuff like that.

01:08:14.880 --> 01:08:18.560
So again, it's about sort of
serving the right experience

01:08:18.560 --> 01:08:20.210
to the right context
and stuff.

01:08:20.210 --> 01:08:24.090
But by assuming less upfront,
you're not forcing mobile

01:08:24.090 --> 01:08:28.700
users to download all this
JavaScript to render an iFrame

01:08:28.700 --> 01:08:29.850
by default.

01:08:29.850 --> 01:08:32.380
And as a result, you're able to
just sort of take bandwidth

01:08:32.380 --> 01:08:34.819
into consideration.

01:08:34.819 --> 01:08:37.880
At the very least, if everything
fails, they have a

01:08:37.880 --> 01:08:41.950
link to Google Maps, and I'd
trust Google Developers on the

01:08:41.950 --> 01:08:46.430
Maps mobile team more than me
to make sure that people can

01:08:46.430 --> 01:08:47.740
get to where they need to get.

01:08:47.740 --> 01:08:48.630
PETE LEPAGE: Absolutely.

